Cape Town -  A Khayelitsha family is seeking answers following the discovery of their relative’s body dumped behind the Homba Primary School on Monday.  Abongile Mahashe, 27, was found murdered, with his mouth and hands tied and wrapped in a brown blanket. His family said they last saw him on Saturday night when he went out from his home in Y Section. “On Monday, when he did not return we started looking around for him,” said the deceased’s sister Phelokazi Mahashe.  “We heard about a body found behind the school, but people did not know it was him. He was wrapped in a blanket and tied with a tape. It looked like he tried fighting his killers but they overpowered him.” Abongile was working as an assistant teacher in one of the schools in Khayelitsha. His sister said that the family was broken, and was seeking answers. “The family is hurting and we have so many questions. What did he do? Who would kill my brother like that?” The family is asking anyone who might have information to contact them. “We want closure,” said Phelokazi.  “We just want to know what happened that led to his brutal killing. He was not a troublesome individual. We just want to know what happened.” Police spokesperson Warrant Officer Joseph Swartbooi said the circumstances surrounding the murder was under investigation. “Lingelethu police members attended to a complaint on Monday at around 07:00 in Dyani Crescent. “Upon arrival at the crime scene, they found the body of an unknown male who was tied with wire. The motive for the attack is unknown.  “The unknown suspect(s) fled the scene and are yet to be arrested. The victim was declared deceased on the scene by the medical personnel.” Anyone with information is urged to call Crime Stop on 08600 10111 Weekend Argus